00:34:35.679 --> 00:34:37.429
So my question is,
is there something

00:34:37.429 --> 00:34:41.030
that I can do so that I don't
prep him in the wrong way

00:34:41.030 --> 00:34:43.430
so that when we
reach five, I can

00:34:43.430 --> 00:34:47.110
coach him to be
better [INAUDIBLE],,

00:34:47.110 --> 00:34:48.480
coaching him [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:48.480 --> 00:34:49.646
TREMAINE DU PREEZ: Oh, dear.

00:34:49.646 --> 00:34:53.100
There are no wrongs when
it comes to parenting.

00:34:53.100 --> 00:34:56.080
No, the book is not
only useful from five--

00:34:56.080 --> 00:34:58.810
the coaching conversations
are only useful from five,

00:34:58.810 --> 00:35:00.560
because at that point,
they're able-- they

00:35:00.560 --> 00:35:02.120
have a greater theory of mind.

00:35:02.120 --> 00:35:04.940
They're able to understand
consequences and have

00:35:04.940 --> 00:35:07.304
enough vocabulary
for conversations.

00:35:07.304 --> 00:35:08.720
But in fact, what
the book does is

00:35:08.720 --> 00:35:11.000
it looks at how the
brain develops right

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:12.020
from the beginning.

00:35:12.020 --> 00:35:15.230
And it looks at the foundations
of fluid intelligence, which

00:35:15.230 --> 00:35:18.690
is memory capacity and
processing speed in the brain.

00:35:18.690 --> 00:35:22.040
It also looks at how a baby's
brain develops in response

00:35:22.040 --> 00:35:24.750
to its environment, which
to me was incredible,

00:35:24.750 --> 00:35:28.340
that if you take a child-- which
has happened in many conflict

00:35:28.340 --> 00:35:30.530
countries-- and put
them in an orphanage

00:35:30.530 --> 00:35:33.350
where they do nothing but
sit in a cot all day, devoid

00:35:33.350 --> 00:35:36.080
of love and contact and
music, and their brains

00:35:36.080 --> 00:35:38.960
are actually smaller than
other children's brains.

00:35:38.960 --> 00:35:42.270
Because they haven't had an
environmental stimulation.

00:35:42.270 --> 00:35:45.120
And the connections in our
brain grow from stimulation.

00:35:45.120 --> 00:35:47.270
So actually, we go right
from the very beginning,

00:35:47.270 --> 00:35:48.952
from before your baby can talk.

00:35:48.952 --> 00:35:50.660
And we look at ways
to actually stimulate

00:35:50.660 --> 00:35:53.270
processing speed and
memory capacity, games

00:35:53.270 --> 00:35:54.080
that you can play.

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:55.550
It's all games.

00:35:55.550 --> 00:35:57.604
We look at things like
when my son was young,

00:35:57.604 --> 00:35:58.520
we lived in Singapore.

00:35:58.520 --> 00:35:59.840
And there are the parking lots.

00:35:59.840 --> 00:36:02.780
There'd be 5,000 parking
bays in a parking lot.

00:36:02.780 --> 00:36:04.970
And it would be over 17 floors.

00:36:04.970 --> 00:36:07.230
And you forget where
you parked your car.

00:36:07.230 --> 00:36:09.110
So I would always just
put it on my phone

00:36:09.110 --> 00:36:11.540
so that I knew when I came
out, which floor I was on,

00:36:11.540 --> 00:36:13.072
which parking bay, which color.

00:36:13.072 --> 00:36:15.280
It was kind of a whole list
of things we had to know.

00:36:15.280 --> 00:36:17.420
But eventually, we
played this little game

00:36:17.420 --> 00:36:18.630
where we put the phones away.

00:36:18.630 --> 00:36:21.707
And we said, OK, let's remember
where we parked the car.

00:36:21.707 --> 00:36:23.040
And we would look at the colors.

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:28.880
So we would go, it was number
17 B on the seventh floor.

00:36:28.880 --> 00:36:34.640
And we'd come up with rhymes--
so 17 baboons in the whatever

00:36:34.640 --> 00:36:35.640
it was.

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:38.090
And these are fun things
that are absolutely

00:36:38.090 --> 00:36:39.890
developing that
brain capacity that

00:36:39.890 --> 00:36:42.800
will be so important later
for all these other things

00:36:42.800 --> 00:36:44.280
that your child needs.

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:47.990
So if you're loving your
child, talking to your child,

00:36:47.990 --> 00:36:50.450
and actually spending
time with them

00:36:50.450 --> 00:36:53.540
away from devices and phones
and that sort of thing--

00:36:53.540 --> 00:36:55.430
because a baby can--

00:36:55.430 --> 00:36:57.470
a young child can only
see about 30 centimeters

00:36:57.470 --> 00:36:58.340
in front of them.

00:36:58.340 --> 00:37:00.350
And that is so that
they can focus,

00:37:00.350 --> 00:37:02.670
so that they're actually
not distracted at all.

00:37:02.670 --> 00:37:05.960
And if you can have that quality
face-to-face time talking,

00:37:05.960 --> 00:37:08.200
using words as big as you want.

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:09.410
And let them hear it.

00:37:09.410 --> 00:37:12.317
They don't get that from a TV
show, because-- from cartoons--

00:37:12.317 --> 00:37:14.150
because the facial
expressions and the words

00:37:14.150 --> 00:37:17.300
are not congruent, or
necessarily congruent.

00:37:17.300 --> 00:37:19.790
So it's very important
that they hear us.

00:37:19.790 --> 00:37:23.740
So keep going-- very important
from the very beginning.

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:27.060
It's actually a pivotal age,
that sort of under three.

00:37:27.060 --> 00:37:31.216
In fact, all the critical brain
mass that a child will have

00:37:31.216 --> 00:37:32.840
is fully developed
by three and a half.

