adults, graduate students,

00:37:50.300 --> 00:37:52.610
et cetera, about these skills.

00:37:52.610 --> 00:37:56.720
And how does that differ,
in your experience,

00:37:56.720 --> 00:37:59.644
from coaching a young child,
like your son or someone

00:37:59.644 --> 00:38:02.250
else, some other minor?

00:38:02.250 --> 00:38:03.860
And again, how
might that coaching

00:38:03.860 --> 00:38:06.426
differ from self-teaching
these skills,

00:38:06.426 --> 00:38:08.050
so how might these
different modalities

00:38:08.050 --> 00:38:09.341
to acquire these skills differ?

00:38:09.341 --> 00:38:11.537
And what does that tell us?

00:38:11.537 --> 00:38:13.370
TREMAINE DU PREEZ: OK,
so the big difference

00:38:13.370 --> 00:38:15.830
between working with
young adults and children

00:38:15.830 --> 00:38:18.980
is self-confidence
and self-belief.

00:38:18.980 --> 00:38:21.650
I find that young children
are still very much looking

00:38:21.650 --> 00:38:25.460
to you for the answers,
whereas young adults feel

00:38:25.460 --> 00:38:26.420
they have the answers.

00:38:26.420 --> 00:38:29.030
They just want you to
check on their thinking.

00:38:29.030 --> 00:38:31.820
And that's just two different
modalities, two different ways

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:33.110
of working with them.

00:38:33.110 --> 00:38:36.352
So with young children, you have
to be their choice architect,

00:38:36.352 --> 00:38:37.310
give them the guidance.

00:38:37.310 --> 00:38:38.601
Because they don't know, right?

00:38:38.601 --> 00:38:41.120
They know what they've
experienced from friends and TV

00:38:41.120 --> 00:38:43.040
and superheroes and stuff.

00:38:43.040 --> 00:38:45.860
So there's a lot more in
terms of intervention.

00:38:45.860 --> 00:38:48.581
There's a lot more of
yourself that you put into it.

00:38:48.581 --> 00:38:50.330
Working with young
adults, it's a lot more

00:38:50.330 --> 00:38:54.860
checking what they're thinking
and definitely not telling them

00:38:54.860 --> 00:38:57.620
what you think, unless
they ask, but helping them

00:38:57.620 --> 00:39:00.170
discover for themselves, so
very much like the conversation

00:39:00.170 --> 00:39:04.040
that you heard but actually
asking those questions,

00:39:04.040 --> 00:39:05.840
just probing, probing,
asking, asking,

00:39:05.840 --> 00:39:08.330
letting them go off and
discover, come back, check,

00:39:08.330 --> 00:39:09.920
and work with it.

00:39:09.920 --> 00:39:12.920
And when it comes to
working with yourself,

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:15.890
it's quite difficult. It's the
most difficult of all of them.

00:39:15.890 --> 00:39:20.240
Because you are asking
questions about your thinking

00:39:20.240 --> 00:39:23.850
with the thinking that is
producing the thinking.

00:39:23.850 --> 00:39:25.280
So this is
particularly difficult.

00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:27.130
This is why having
a sounding board--

00:39:27.130 --> 00:39:29.570
not necessarily a coach,
but just somebody to say,

00:39:29.570 --> 00:39:31.050
hey, this is what I'm thinking.

00:39:31.050 --> 00:39:32.100
What do you think?

00:39:32.100 --> 00:39:34.460
How would you find
fault with me?

00:39:34.460 --> 00:39:38.030
So again, it's something--
and I'm doing a PhD now

00:39:38.030 --> 00:39:40.190
in this critical thinking
decision science.

00:39:40.190 --> 00:39:42.890
And what I'm finding,
the foundation of it

00:39:42.890 --> 00:39:45.920
is the ability to be
reflective, to actually say,

00:39:45.920 --> 00:39:46.970
these are my frames.

00:39:46.970 --> 00:39:49.090
This is where I'm coming from.

00:39:49.090 --> 00:39:50.090
But that's what I think.

00:39:50.090 --> 00:39:50.590
Hang on.

00:39:50.590 --> 00:39:51.530
Is that really true?

00:39:51.530 --> 00:39:53.420
Are these actually my
frames, and going back,

00:39:53.420 --> 00:39:55.253
speaking to other people,
checking yourself.

00:39:56.264 --> 00:39:57.680
I have this
particular background.

00:39:57.680 --> 00:39:58.470
This is who I am.

00:39:58.470 --> 00:40:00.020
How does it affect my thinking?

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:01.370
Because that affects
your decision making.

00:40:01.370 --> 00:40:03.500
Because that affects how
you process information.

00:40:03.500 --> 00:40:05.510
So the big difference
in working with yourself

00:40:05.510 --> 00:40:07.430
is brutal honesty.

00:40:07.430 --> 00:40:10.260
And that, my friend, is the
hardest thing in the world.

00:40:10.260 --> 00:40:11.285
But it's doable.

00:40:11.285 --> 00:40:11.970
Yeah.

